                     <interp inst="def1-1368-18360509" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM RATCLIFFE</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18360509-1368-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18360509-1368-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18360509-1368-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp> for stealing, on the <rs id="t18360509-cd-209" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360509-1368-offence-1 t18360509-cd-209"></join>29th of April</rs>, 1 sovereign, the monies of <persName id="t18360509-name-1455" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1455" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1455" type="surname" value="ANNAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1455" type="given" value="PETER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1455" type="occupation" value="confectioner"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360509-1368-offence-1 t18360509-name-1455"></join>Peter Annand</persName>, his master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1456" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1456" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1456" type="surname" value="ANNAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1456" type="given" value="PETER"></interp>PETER ANNAND</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at Bridge-road, Lambeth, and am a confectioner. The prisoner was in my employ for about ten days—I saw this sovereign safe in the till about nine o'clock at night on the 29th of April, and missed it before ten o'clock, I immediately made inquiries of the prisoner—he denied having it—when he had got his great coat on, and was going away, I called him back—he waited in my parlour till I fetched a constable—he still denied having it, but the constable found it in his waistcoat pocket—he then said he picked it up from under the counter.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner</hi>. I found it under the counter—I did not know whose it was—my master did not ask me if I had got it till the policeman came. Witness. I did—he said he had not got it, that he had seen it in the till, but he did not know where it was.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183605090258"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1457" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1457" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1457" type="surname" value="ALESBURY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1457" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS ALESBURY</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable L</hi> 136.) I was called in, and the prosecutor said to him, "Have you got the sovereign?"—the prisoner said no, he had not—I found it in his waistcoat pocket, among some halfpence—he then said he had picked it up on the floor, and asked forgiveness of his master.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character.)</p>
